## Building the Snake Game in React

**Mental model:** The snake is an array of `{x,y}` cells; the head is index 0. Each tick you prepend a new head in the current direction and pop the tail — unless you ate food, in which case you keep the tail (grow). Direction lives in a `ref` so the keydown handler always reads the latest value (avoiding stale closures), and you reject 180° reversals.

### Step 1 — Snake, direction, food
```jsx
const [snake, setSnake] = useState([{ x: 7, y: 7 }]);
const dir = useRef({ x: 1, y: 0 });
const [food, setFood] = useState({ x: 3, y: 3 });
```

### Step 2 — Tick: move head, grow or shift
```jsx
setSnake((s) => {
  const head = { x: s[0].x + dir.current.x, y: s[0].y + dir.current.y };
  if (hitsWall(head) || hitsSelf(head, s)) { setOver(true); return s; }
  const grew = head.x === food.x && head.y === food.y;
  const next = [head, ...s];
  if (grew) setFood(randomCell()); else next.pop();
  return next;
});
```

### Step 3 — Keyboard with reversal guard
```jsx
const set = (d) => { if (d.x !== -dir.current.x || d.y !== -dir.current.y) dir.current = d; };
```

### Step 4 — Interval loop + cleanup
```jsx
useEffect(() => { const id = setInterval(tick, 150); return () => clearInterval(id); }, [over]);
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| 180° reversal | Reject if new dir is opposite. |
| Stale direction | Keep dir in a `ref`, not state. |
| Food on snake | Re-roll until off the snake. |

**Interview tip:** Storing direction in a `ref` is the key insight — a state-based direction read inside the interval closure would be stale, causing the classic "snake ignores my turn" bug.

