## Building the Snake Game in Angular

**Mental model:** The snake is an array of `{x,y}`; head at index 0. Each tick prepend a new head and pop the tail — unless food was eaten (grow). Direction is a field read inside the tick; reject 180° reversals. Clear the interval and key listener in `ngOnDestroy`. Classic `NgModule` setup, no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — State + direction
```typescript
snake = [{ x: 7, y: 7 }];
food = { x: 3, y: 3 };
dir = { x: 1, y: 0 };
over = false;
```

### Step 2 — Tick
```typescript
tick(): void {
  const head = { x: this.snake[0].x + this.dir.x, y: this.snake[0].y + this.dir.y };
  if (this.hits(head)) { this.over = true; clearInterval(this.id); return; }
  const grew = head.x === this.food.x && head.y === this.food.y;
  const next = [head, ...this.snake];
  if (grew) { this.score++; this.food = this.randomFree(next); } else { next.pop(); }
  this.snake = next;
}
```

### Step 3 — Keyboard with reversal guard
```typescript
@HostListener('window:keydown', ['$event'])
onKey(e: KeyboardEvent): void { /* map arrows, reject opposite */ }
```

### Step 4 — Lifecycle
```typescript
ngOnInit(): void { this.id = setInterval(() => this.tick(), 150); }
ngOnDestroy(): void { clearInterval(this.id); }
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| 180° reversal | Reject opposite. |
| Food on snake | Re-roll until free. |
| Cleanup | `ngOnDestroy` clears the interval. |

**Interview tip:** `@HostListener('window:keydown')` for input plus an interval started in `ngOnInit` and cleared in `ngOnDestroy` is the clean Angular game loop — the lifecycle teardown is the part to emphasize.

